318—323: if as some say the all-environing ether begets all things and takes them back at death, then must it be mortal3 for it is thus subject to increase and decrease.—This passage is an argumentum ad hominem: the notion pleases his poetical fancy, and he has already more than once seized on the thought and given to it an epicurean turn 3 see what has been said at 1 250, and especially 11 991 foll. which has much resemblance to this, caelesti sumus omnes semine oriundi, and 1000 quod missumst ex aetheris oris cet.: the consciousness of this prevents him from giving a denial to the theory here 3 and he contents himself with leaving it as hypothetical τ si procreat cet. in which there is doubtless irony mixed.
